<hr/>
<div id='channel-anchor' class='row-fluid panel'>
    <h3>Channel</h3>
    <h5 id='channel-name-anchor'>Name</h5>
    The name field is just a reference name for the Channel. Choosing a unique name is wise so you can tell them apart in the list.
    <h5 id='channel-notify-anchor'>Notify User/Email</h5>
    The notify feature will notify either the user by their chosen method of being notified, or to a given email address.
    <h5 id='channel-processor-anchor'>Run Processor</h5>
    If the "Run Processor" option is ticked, then the System will automatically run the matching Channel processors after it has run
    the read cycle. If this is left unticked, then the processor will need to be called manually.
</div>
<br/>
<div id='email-anchor' class='row-fluid panel'>
    <h3>Email</h3>
    <h5 id='email-protocol-anchor'>Protocol</h5>
    The protocol list is either POP3 or IMAP, choose the one relevant to the email account used.
    <h5 id='email-server-anchor'>Server URL</h5>
    The server url is the POP3 or IMAP server url to your email service, for example, Gmail's server url is [pop3|imap].gmail.com.
    <h5 id='email-username-anchor'>Username and Password</h5>
    The username and password for the email account used.
    <h5 id='email-port-anchor'>Port</h5>
    The port for the email account used.
    <h5 id='email-useauth-anchor'>Use Auth</h5>
    The use auth flag is to tell the system whether or not to use an SSL connection.
    <h5 id='email-username-anchor'>Folder</h5>
    The folder specifies where to get emails from within the account. Leave blank for Inbox, research will need to be done to find
    the right syntax for specifying folders.
</div>
<br/>
<div id='filter-anchor' class='row-fluid panel'>
    <h3>Filter</h3>
    <h5 id='filter-to-anchor'>To, From and CC</h5>
    The to, from and cc fields are the email addresses that we want to get emails to and from. For example if we wanted only get emails 
    that have been sent from "user@example.com" then put "user@example.com" in the FROM field.
    <h5 id='filter-subject-anchor'>Subject</h5>
    The subject filter field, is the same as above except we can filter by the subject field. For example, if we wanted to only read 
    emails with a subject "JOBS", then put "JOBS" in the subject filter field.
    <h5 id='filter-body-anchor'>Body</h5>
    Like above, the body filter will only retrieve emails where the body contains some text specified.
</div>
<br/>
<div id='action-anchor' class='row-fluid panel'>
    <h3>Action</h3>
    <h5 id='action-action-anchor'>Post Read Action</h5>
    The post read action is the name of an action to run after the channel has been read.
    <h5 id='faction-data-anchor'>Post Read Data</h5>
    The post read data is what data should be sent to the above specified action.
</div>
